What external factors are there in building a more successful startup?

Timothy Nguyen & Jacob Yang

5/6/2021

Why is it important?

  • Startups are full of promise and excitement, but the flip side is, theyre also full of risk and uncertainty. There are a lot of great ideas out there that somehow never get off the ground, and, conversely, there are plenty of questionable ones that become massive successes.

  • In addition to a good idea, there are many factors that influence a startups success, and understanding and leveraging these factors will help a startup get further along the road to success.

  • In this project, we will focus on some external factors that may affect a startups developement:

    • Category of industries, locations, investors

Why is it important?

  • If youre looking to build a startup, understanding where to begin your startup may be important based off the industry youre in.
  • Successful can mean many things. It can mean being operated and become a series C or higher startup. Maybe you want to build a company that IPO or accquired. Are there specific industries or locations where you can find your success?
  • What investors could be important to your business?

Notes:

  • Weve filtered our data to look at USA locations
  • Were only looking at data from companies who have had their last funding round between 2013 and 2015.
  • Reason: Investor patterns change quite rapidly and what made a company successful five years ago doesnt neccesarily mean much for your success now (if we were living in 2015/2016)

Datasets (Companies Side)

  • company name, funding_total_usd, status, country_code, state_code, city, funding_rounds, last_funding_year

Datasets (Investors side)

  • investor_name, state_code, category (industry), funded_Year, raised_amount_usd

Startups locations - Companies.R

Investor Interactive plots - Investors.R

## Listening on http://127.0.0.1:3599

Conclusions

  • Most startups especially those that are acquired/ipo happen in the east and west coast

  • Within the past 2-3 years, those who have gone to ipo/acquired were primarily those in the software/internet sector or biotech area

  • For different industries, the main investors are different:

    • Biotechnology: Domain Associates, OrbiMed Advisors

    • Hotels: Baillie Gifford, China Broadband Capital, FIdelity Investments

    • Enterprise Software: Andreessen Horowitz, Insight Venture Partners

    • Analytics: RRE Ventures, DFJ Growth, Jefferies & Company
